<section>
  <h2 class="kicker">The vision</h2>
  <h3>Eventually, every flight broadcast over ADS-L.</h3>

  <h3>Aircraft to aircraft</h3>
  <p>
    Visibility starts with no infrastructure at all: two skyBlips see each
    other directly, aircraft to aircraft. Every device in the air makes the
    sky a little more readable for everyone else: the network grows more
    useful with every equipped cockpit.
  </p>

  <h3>Gliders, already visible</h3>
  <p>
    Soaring equipped itself long ago: most gliders transmit over FLARM,
    tracked on the ground by the Open Glider Network. skyBlip connects to
    that ecosystem instead of competing with it: the skyBlips receive
    FLARM-equipped gliders directly in flight, the traffic tracked by OGN is
    part of the picture the skyPost stations relay to cockpits, and what the
    skyPosts hear is published back to OGN.
  </p>

  <h3>Flying clubs, the natural relays</h3>
  <p>
    Every airfield is a high point with power and people who fly. A skyPost
    station on the clubhouse roof covers the field, the circuit and the
    countryside around it. The network densifies club by club, the way OGN
    was built glider by glider. Where there is no club and no mains power,
    the solar station mounts on a simple mast.
  </p>

  <h3>The goal</h3>
  <p>
    Every flight (light aircraft, microlight, glider, paramotor, drone)
    broadcast over <strong>ADS-L</strong>, the open European standard, and
    visible to all the others. Not through regulatory mandate: because the
    equipment will have become the obvious choice: affordable,
    interoperable, and useful from the very first flight.
  </p>
</section>

